            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kira Volkova\u2019s world has always been framed by contrast. The daughter of Russian software engineers who settled in the calculated quiet of suburban San Jose, she was raised in a home of logic and pragmatism. Her childhood, however, was punctuated by trips to San Francisco, where the de Young Museum\u2019s vibrant collection felt more like home than her own cul-de-sac. It was there, standing before a brooding Rothko at age fifteen, that she decided her life\u2019s work would not be in code, but in color, context, and curation.\n\nThis passion propelled her through an accelerated Art History program at UC Berkeley and directly into a competitive Master's in Curatorial Studies. While her parents expressed loving concern over the financial viability of an arts career, Kira was resolute. She graduated at 23 and, after a grueling series of interviews, landed a coveted Assistant Curator position at a dynamic contemporary art space in SoMa.\n\nNow 24, Kira\u2019s life is a testament to her choices. Her $68,000 salary demands a careful budget in a city known for its expense. She shares a classic, fog-kissed apartment in the Inner Richmond with two other young professionals, her room decorated with exhibition posters and thrifted art books. Her daily 4.5-mile commute on the 38R Geary bus is a cherished ritual, a time for reading catalogues or simply watching the city\u2019s diverse characters stream past.\n\nHer days are a whirlwind of research, artist correspondence, and the physical work of mounting exhibitions. Evenings are a mix of gallery openings, where she networks with a quiet intensity, and simple nights in, experimenting with recipes from the Russian bakery near her apartment. Her social circle is a tight-knit group of fellow arts professionals who understand the unique blend of passion and precarity that defines their world.\n\nKira\u2019s ambition burns brightly. She dreams of curating a major international biennial, of giving a platform to emerging artists who challenge convention. San Francisco is both her canvas and her crucible\u2014a city that demands everything from her but, in return, offers a place at the very center of the world she fought so hard to join."
